Authoritative Repo VM workflow
Stage 1 — Build the Rocky Linux foundation

Start with:

Fresh Rocky Linux 9 Server with GUI
Good Internet connectivity
Static or temporary working network
Adequate disk space

Then run:

LinuxInfra-v0.7.2.zip

Select the:

Repo Server role

This stage prepares:

Hostname, IP address, gateway and DNS
Timezone and NTP
Base operating-system packages
Firewall
SELinux
Docker Engine and Docker Compose
Repo VM base infrastructure

After LinuxInfra reports success, reboot once:

sudo reboot

Then confirm:

hostnamectl
ip -br address
getenforce
systemctl is-active firewalld
systemctl is-active docker
docker version
docker compose version
Stage 2 — Build the Mailcow prerequisite RPM repositories

Run:

repoinfra-mailcow-repo-rebuild-1.1.1.tar.gz

The order should be:

bash ./bin/package-self-check.sh
sudo bash ./run.sh --dry-run
sudo bash ./run.sh

This stage prepares:

Apache repository service
/rpms/base
/rpms/mailcow
Mailcow host prerequisite RPMs
Complete Git dependency chain
Repository metadata
SELinux labels for repository content
HTTP publication
Client repository definition
Rollback information

However, you reported three failures in this package. Therefore:

Do not proceed to Stage 3 until we review those three failures and Stage 2 completes with Overall status: PASS.

Stage 3 depends on the directories, Apache aliases and repository structure created by Stage 2.

Stage 3 — Build the complete offline Mailcow annex

After Stage 2 passes, run:

repoinfra-mailcow-complete-offline-annex-1.0.0.tar.gz

Again use:

bash ./bin/package-self-check.sh
sudo bash ./run.sh --dry-run
sudo bash ./run.sh

This stage adds:

Docker CE offline RPM repository
Docker Compose and related RPMs
Exact Mailcow source bundle
All Mailcow container images
Compressed image archive
Container image manifests
Image IDs, tags and digests
SHA-256 checksums
Offline Mail Server installation script
Versioned /images and /manifests publication

After this stage passes, the Repo VM will be ready for a new Mail Server VM to install Mailcow without downloading the large container images from the Internet.

